 "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1287.752","u": "Yes. They gave us tickets."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1288.788","u": "Tickets."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1289.424","u": "We were given money."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1291.577","u": "Where did you travel?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1294.271","u": "We traveled . . . At that time the army was founded, Anders Army, Sikorski-Anders Army . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1300.965","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1301.275","u": ". . . was founded at that time. Then all the Jews served in the Polish Army. Those who . . . for the most part they traveled to Buzuluk, to Totskoye. That is where the army was being formed; the Army was being founded. When we got there a new Diaspora started, a new, fresh Diaspora. There one first felt that one was a Jew."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1324.632","u": "Hmm."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1325.590","u": "Yes. We were punished there. If one asked for a bit of soup, we caught a bone in the head and we got a good slap. Every step we took was taking a risk. It was not bearable. A lot of Jews served in the Polish Army and they could not take it, so they left the Polish Army. Then again, many went with the Army to Iran."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1349.848","u": "Where?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1350.739","u": "To Iran. They traveled to Iran."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1352.096","u": "Ooh. Tell me, how was it by the Russians there? Did they beat [people]?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1359.026","u": "By the Russians? No, I did not see [that]. I was not beaten."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1362.641","u": "It was difficult to work, but they did not beat [people]."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1365.459","u": "No, they did not beat [people]. But if one did not make one&#39;s quota, that which one had to make . . . then, of course, one became sick, because one could not get any food. Those people who could not meet their quota. [Among] those people who could not meet their quota . . . one was a lawyer, one was a doctor and one was a dental technician, who had to chop wood, but he could not make his quota, so he became weak."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1387.993","u": "Where did you go to then?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1389.940","u": "We went to Central Asia."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1392.777","u": "You went into the Army?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1395.929","u": "We went into the Army. The Army did not know what to do with us, because it didn&#39;t have any place, any place for so many. The Army fed us quite well, but a Jew was [despised?]. They couldn&#39;t stand to look at a Jew, and Jews had to run away from there, and everyone went to Central Asia, because there in Middle Asia it was warm and there it was very cold."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1424.086","u": "Aha, yes . . ."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1424.827","u": "So it turned out . . . then it turned out that we were already in winter there . . . [break in wire] . . . in Central Asia. [unintelligible] but there in Central Asia it was the same thing. Sikorski&#39;s Army was also there. One could also go into the Army there, but there were also a lot of mistakes when one went into the Army. On the day that the Army left for Iran, they told the Jews to take off their uniforms. They remained in Central Asia while they left. Many of us became ill. I came down with typhus. I was in the hospital for seven weeks."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1462.305","u": "What is typhus? Typhus?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1463.590","u": "Typhus, yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1464.709","u": "From lice."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1465.383","u": "Lice, yes. Typhus. Then I contracted dysentery. Then I got diarrhea. I was in the hospital for five months."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1475.871","u": "What kind of hospital? Polish?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1478.393","u": "It was good that it was a military hospital. The Russians . . . the Russians . . . the doctors were Russian and the staff was Russian, but it was a hospital, a military hospital, and it was named for the Army, Sikorski&#39;s Army. We were treated quite well there. We were fed quite well there. Those who survived, survived . . . and we left."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1511.956","u": "Well, when did you get out?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1514.552","u": "I got out of the hospital and I went to . . . at that time there opened relief agency; they were Polish agencies for support. It was support from the British. People began to receive support. Every refugee who arrived and showed that he had been in a camp, a Polish one, began to receive support. It was. . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1540.402","u": "It was a Russian camp."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1542.055","u": "Yes, a Russian camp."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1544.269","u": "[In Russian] A certificate."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1545.536","u": "[In Yiddish] He showed that he had been in a camp. He registered. There was an office in every city. One received soap, one received money, one received clothes, shoes, one received . . . they were given [unintelligible]."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1559.580","u": "[unintelligible]"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1560.344","u": "Yes. But those who went to work got the best things. Those who did not go to work had no right to receive [anything], unless they were sick and the doctor cured them. At that time one could get [something] only if he went to work. I . . . during the course of the day, I had to work even though I was unable to, because if I didn&#39;t . . . Without working I couldn&#39;t have survived, but I did thanks to what I received from these relief offices. Even sick, I had to work. I worked until . . . after working I once again got swollen feet. There was a doctor from Warsaw . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1597.306","u": "Where did your feet become swollen? On the sides? Show me."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1599.976","u": "At the bottom. He said that this was due to a weakened heart."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1602.342","u": "Oh . . ."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1604.258","u": "From the heart, from the heart. He said that I was not allowed to work anymore. He sent me to a convalescent home. There was a convalescent home in Gusar, Central Asia. There was also a relief agency there. Jews. People there did not work. It was figured that one would spend three or four weeks there resting. The food they served was quite good. Then a decree was issued (this was in &#39;43 in the month of March) saying that all Polish people had to accept Russian passports . . . become Russian citizens. If not . . . many were arrested."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1654.539","u": "[unintelligible]"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1655.574","u": "Yes. I didn&#39;t want to think too much about it. I was, by this time, afraid. I had spent fourteen months in jail, so I immediately got a passport, and as soon as I got the passport, I . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1666.972","u": "To be a Russian citizen."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1668.030","u": "To be a Russian citizen. I began to work, and I worked. It wasn&#39;t bad."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1676.037","u": "[unintelligible] the Polish relief agencies?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1682.784","u": "No. At that time all the relief agencies were disbanded. All the relief agencies were liquidated, and no more Polish relief agencies existed. Then we really had to go to work, and we went to work. Whatever one had the strength to do, but one had to take a passport. One could not exist without a passport. As soon as one got a passport . . . they took people and sent them to the front."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1712.647","u": "What was that?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1714.039","u": "That means . . . a front, that is called a job . . . a mobilization of . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1722.064","u": "A mobilization to work."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1724.073","u": "To work."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1724.870","u": "And where did you work?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1726.198","u": "Me . . . various things. I was sent to [Astroyik?]. This is near Tashkent [unintelligible]."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1734.230","u": "Not to the front."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1736.463","u": "No. Behind the front. All of this was behind. One person was sent [unintelligible] another was sent to [unintelligible] work. So everyone took passports and he began to work. Now we had the right to live in the city. We improved everything. We were there in &#39;43, &#39;44, &#39;45 . . . until the end of the war. When the war ended, we once again heard news that people were traveling to Poland."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1770.704","u": "With Russian passports?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1772.707","u": "The Russian passports were taken back. They gave out a document, half in Polish, half in Russian. And at the border . . . we went home to Poland. . .at the border they took back the Russian document and the passport. They took everything away. All that remained was a small document written in Polish. We went home to Poland with transport and we arrived in Poland in the month of . . . July."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1810.258","u": "&#39;46?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1811.242","u": "&#39;46."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1813.393","u": "So late?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1814.488","u": "Yes, yes. The last transport."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1817.028","u": "July &#39;46?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1817.715","u": "Yes, yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "x1818.773","u": "July &#39;46? That was four weeks ago."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1819.664","u": "Four weeks ago. Yes, yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1822.482","u": "Well?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1823.038","u": "What is it today?"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1824.447","u": "What is it? September already."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1825.966","u": "September . . . well."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1826.930","u": "Two months."},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1827.451","u": "Two months. When we arrived in Poland . . . we thought that we would be able to exist at home. Poland was, after all, our home. We had lived there for so many years . . . our fathers, our grandfathers. But we were told that we could not go out into the street."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1846.001","u": "Who said that? Other Jews?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1848.060","u": "The Jews who came to meet the train. Jews came out to meet the train said that we should not loiter in the street, because there had been some shooting today. At night a train went through going to Warsaw-Lublin, and four Jews were taken off. No one knew what had happened. In the morning it was discovered that they had been shot."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1868.929","u": "In which city was it that you arrived when you came home?"},    {"who": "Joseph [last name unknown]", "start": "1871.843","u": "[Mielec?]"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1872.139","u": "[In English] This concludes Spool 158 with the report of a Mr. Joseph, and we will continue Spool 159. Illinois Institute of Technology wire recording. Wiesbaden, September the 26th, 19&#226; . . . eh, 25th, September the 25th, 1946. Illinois Institute of Technology wire recording."}        ]
